text:
As a real Swiss travel expert, yes I can confirm, Switzerland can be expensive. If you book a hotel in touristic hotspot at the last minute, you can pay 300 or more. But you can also pay half that price or much less, if you spend a few minutes online on a good hotel booking website a few weeks ahead, or just book a less fancy hotel in the next village, or a hostel.
Also Switzerland has one of the top 2 best public transport networks worldwide, and this is absolutely true (1st beeing Japan?).  You can get almost everywhere in Switzerland by train, by bus, by tramway, by boat, at least every half hour or every hour. And I can tell you that renting a car to travel into tourist hotspots would be just ridicolous for most of us locals. Because it is more stresful than using trains, and because you have to drive and keep your eyes on the road for hours, while you can have a nap in the train or enjoy the nice view in a train, and you will arrive more relaxed than in a car. And it is going to be cheaper than renting  that expensive fancy car, because there are travel passes for tourists. If every tourist would use a car to get to Interlaken or further, we would have to build 8-lane highways like in the U.S.. And obviously our clean alpine mountain air would be totally poluted because of all those cars. And that's why some mountain villages can't be reached by car, like Zermatt or Wengen! To keep the air clean from dirty cars! Absolutely true! Be smarter and use public transport network in Switzerland.
And yes, fancy restaurants in tourist hotspots can be expensive, but there are always cheaper alternatives. Or just buy your food in a grocery store like we Swiss do. You can buy high quality organic food in every village (Migros/Coop), and it is still 5-10 times cheaper than in that fancy restaurant.
And earning 125k a year is just fake news, maybe one of ten people earns that much, must people earn around 60k-90k.
Greetins from Z√ºrich, Switzerland

text:
I live in NZ but my mum is swiss and I've visited a few times.

The scenery is incredible and I say this as someone who lives on one of the prettiest harbours in the world (Wellington!)

The Swiss might seem a little bit 'uptight' or conservative but they are actually a very quiet respectful culture who don't approve of showoffs and rudeness.  If you behave decently you will be treated with courtesy and kindness.

Yes it is expensive, but they choose to pay ppl properly and not use migration to exploit people (either foreign or local) so the tradeoff is that you are generally a LOT safe than in other parts of the world and I never thought twice about walking home alone in the dark.

Get away from the obvious tourist centers if you can and just visit any number of random villages and towns along the way between the major places...try your luck and you will probably find a place and memories that you will never forget!

Walking along a lake and popping into some random hotel or hostel when your feet are sore is a perfect weekend!

text:
Lucerne is actually the most beautiful city (Bern and Solothurn, Schaffhausen and Stein am Rhein are nice, too, though).
There is a super touristy part where accommodation is rather luxurious and expensive but like 500m (because it's a small place) away from that super touristy spot you'll find cheaper accommodation, especially air b'n'b or simple old school b'n'b, also you'll find yourself in the middle of Switzerland and everything beautiful and interesting (German and Italian part) is roughly 100km in any direction. 
You can hop on a train "the Voralpenexpress" and travel to Lake Constance in one day and back and have the most beautiful Alpine crossing view.
The next day you hop on a train and visit Bern and so on.
Also the night life is great in Lucerne. You'll find everything you want here and very nice metropolitan people in a rather small, but immensely beautiful city.

Protip. Don't rent a car in switzerland. You almost certainly won't need it because switzerland has the best, most efficient, reliable and luxurious trains in the world. They can take you to basically anywhere in the country, even small towns with only a few thousand people. 

And its all wayyy cheaper. A 15 day inclusive pass to everywhere is switzerland is only 460 usd, vs 2700 in that "cheapest" rental car. That 6 times cheaper!  Even first class is only 700 bucks or 4 times cheaper.

text: Switzerland consistently ranks as one of the safest countries in the world. The streets are clean, and crime rates are low. Swiss society is characterized by its efficiency and precision. The country is known for its punctuality, reliable public transport, and a strong work ethic.Switzerland is a winter wonderland and a paradise for skiers and snowboarders. It offers some of the best skiing resorts in the world. The Swiss enjoy an excellent quality of life, with high standards of healthcare, education, and overall well-being.Switzerland is home to several international organizations, including the United Nations and the Red Cross.Whether you're interested in exploring the outdoors, indulging in culinary delights, or simply enjoying the Swiss way of life, Switzerland offers a wide range of experiences for visitors and residents alike. text:
It's definitely not. We have a MASSIVE problem with dwindling diversity of animals. As example, as a kid i lived near a little brook. There were frogs, toads, little waterspiders, salamanders, newts, dragonflies etc etc etc. Nowadays, the same brook is devoid of live besides maybe the odd confused toad, haven't seen a dragonfly in years and the only thing really proliferating are wasps. The local cats when suddenly every family traded their dog for a little mass murder machine because the local forests became nature protection zones and dog walking got severly limited there. They killed off about 70-80% of the local birds within a decade. I'd sit outside with a bird-encyclopedia and try to figure out which bird i just saw hopping through our lawn as a kid. Now it's just common tits and ravens and bussards, which are too big for the cats to hunt. The ground has a fuckton of contaminations due to years of ignorant malpractices which ends up everywhere. 

The changing climate is taking a heavy toll as well, as some of the more alpine flora and fauna, both small and large, are now struggling badly due to higher temperatures. 

That being said, there are alot of projects, ideas and work done to figure out how to stop this rapid decline.

text: Been to Switzerland, every place hes mentioned & more. Zermatt is also a must see. And a couple days in Zurich dont hurt either. Mt Pilatus, Murren, Schilthorn, the amazing train rides through the mountains. Hiring a car is good, but honestly felt the train rides & just travelling around with a daypack (luggage in hotel ofc) is the best way to see switzerland. As far as it being really expensive, sure is. But why everyone whining about it being expensive, just save up & cut back on other things & not go to other places, until you can comfortably enjoy switzerland. Why would you want to half ass a hobby? Thats just stupid. I wanted to travel heaps in my teens & early twenties, when most people were doing cheap contiki tours which didnt take you to any places really worth visiting and time spent was barely nothing. But they went for the sake of it just to tick off something on an imaginary list. Now at 28, after working on my career & self, I comfortably travel to all these locations & more and actually enjoy my stay & not be frustrated & restricted by things such as expensive food in Swiss. I'm by no means a millionaire, but just be smart about it, travelling for the sake of it aint fun, why would you want to spend thousands & avoid all the touristy places, makes no sense.. just so you can say "oh I went switzerland too for a fraction of the cost" but did nothing of note lol... I'd rather enjoy spending $5k, then wasting $3k. Thing is, dont fall into the trap of thinking your behind in life just because someone else has done more & seen more.. do it at your own pace & you will enjoy it all

text: The most perfect country in the world for now is still the USA, like it or not. Where else can you get the strongest economy on the planet, the best medical facilities, awesome nature (the grand canyon, Yosemite, beautiful beaches, Hawaii, national parks, Aspen, Niagara Falls, etc. etc.), the strongest military, the best music / art / entertainment, the best graduate study / research facilities, the highest information technology, etc, etc., and yet the cost of living is very very very VERY affordable. text:
Avoid to rent a car if you don't really need it and probably, as a tourist, you don't need it.
If the car you rent was 180CHF per day, with that same price you can buy the half tax for trains and many other transportations for a whole year (and probably they have some special offers for tourists, ask the SBB/CFF/FFS), and you can buy tickets for about the half price (is not always half). So if you plan to stay for long, maybe is a better option.
For the Hotels and Restaurants, yes they are expensive in Switzerland, but they are particularly expensive in tourist areas (traps?), so try to search for something out of those areas and you will enjoy more affordable restaurants and hotels, but I understand that one of the beautiful things to be a tourist is to enjoy tourists activities (but in that case, you have to accept the price).

text: Thanks to the author of the channel for this fascinating video! It is interesting to see how people live in other countries! It is very important to know foreign languages on such trips. I would like to recommend to all travelers a practical guide to learning foreign languages by Yuriy Ivantsiv "Polyglot Notes. Practical tips for learning foreign languages". This book contains a lot of useful tips on how to learn a foreign language for tourists, students, entrepreneurs and anyone who needs a foreign language in life. There are a lot of good tips on how to solve problems with the language from beginner to advanced level of language learning. It turns out that the traveler only needs to know a few dialogues and you can easily travel around the world! You don't have to spend a lot of time to fully learn a foreign language, you just need to learn what you can use when you travel. I wish everyone exciting travels!

text:
If you die tonight, do you know where you're going? Did you know that Jesus Christ is THE only way to Heaven and He loves you? 
Through Him, God offers you a FREE gift ‚Äì forgiveness. All you need to do is repent, turn away from your sins and evil ways, 
from now on put your faith completely in Jesus Christ and be obedient to Him.

Biblical explanation of the Gospel:

God doesn‚Äôt want anybody in hell because He loves us, but you must understand why
we deserve hell and why those who refuse to live under His authority will go
there. (Matthew 12:30) ''Whoever is not with me is against me, and whoever does not 
gather with me scatters.'' He gave us the law (Ten Commandments) not to make us righteouss, but
rather to show us our sin (Romans 3:20). God gave us free will and since Adam
sinned in the garden, sin is the nature of our flesh and we ALL have sinned. (Romans 3:23) 
The law demands death to those who sin (Romans 6:23). 
For someone to be justified before holy God they have to be sinless, that's why everyone need Jesus Christ
for He lived a sinless life.


None of us are good in God‚Äôs eyes, because for God good means moral perfection. We all
have broken God‚Äôs commandments, we all have sinned in our lives so none of us
are good. ‚Äò‚ÄôFor whoever keeps the whole law and yet stumbles at just one point is
guilty of breaking all of it.‚Äô‚Äô (James 2:10). 


Good News is that Jesus Christ lived a perfect, holy, sinless life, Christ died for our sins according to the Scriptures, 
He was buried and He was raised from the dead on the third day according to the Scriptures (1 Corinthians 15:3-4)
For God so loved the world that He gave His one and only Son, that whoever
believes in Him shall not perish but have eternal life.‚Äô‚Äô (John 3:16) 
We aren‚Äôt saved based on our good deeds/works, but only by the grace of God through faith. 
''For it is by grace you have been saved, through faith - and this is not from yourselves, it is the gift of God -
not by works, so that no one can boast. (Ephesians 2:8-9) 
Jesus said ‚Äò‚Äôit is finished‚Äô‚Äô (John 19:30) just before He died on the cross, which means He paid the fine for our sins
(past, present, future) to be forgiven if we repent and trust in Him.


''What then? Shall we sin because we are not under law but under grace? Certainly not!'' (Romans 6:15)
''Repent therefore and be converted, that your sins may be blotted out'' (Acts 3:19)
Repentance is a turning away from sin and all evil works, and it always results in changed behavior (Luke 3:8). 
Biblically, a person who repents does not continue willfully in sin.
While sorrow from sin is not equivalent to repentance, it is certainly an element of scriptural repentance (2 Corinthians 7:10). 
Do not play a hypocrite. ''God is light; in Him there is no darkness at all. 
If we claim to have fellowship with Him and yet walk in the darkness, we lie and do not live out the truth.'' (1 John 1:5-6)


If you have repented and have genuine faith in Jesus Christ then you will receive the gift of Holy Spirit and be born-again spiritually. 
(John 3:3) Jesus replied, "Very truly I tell you, no one can see the kingdom of God unless they are born again." 
When you believed, you were marked in Him with a seal, the promised Holy Spirit, who is a deposit guaranteeing our inheritance 
until the redemption of those who are God‚Äôs possession - to the praise of His glory. (Ephesians 1:13-14)
You are born again with the Spirit of Christ (2 Corinthians 5:17). 
Whoever believes in the Son has eternal life; whoever does not obey the Son shall not see life, but the wrath of God remains on him. (John 3:36)


''You will know them by their fruits'' (Matthew 7)
If you have been truly born-again with the Holy Spirit and He has regenerated your heart, you will desire righteousness - 
to do what is good and righteous in God's eyes, to seek God everyday in His Word and prayer, to strengthen your relationship with God.
You will no longer desire to willfully continue living in sin but will want to obey God out of your love for Him because of His amazing grace
revealed to us through the death and resurrection of His Son.
''Therefore, if anyone is in Christ, he is a new creation; old things have passed away; behold, all things have become new.'' (2 Corinthians 5:17)
''For we are His workmanship, created in Christ Jesus for good works, which God prepared beforehand that we should walk in them.'' (Eph 2:10)
You will have a testimony - of what your life had been before and how has it changed now when you have surrendered it to Lord Jesus Christ.


As a declaration and affirmation of your faith in Jesus Christ, get baptised in water because He commanded us to do so.
In John 3:5 Jesus answered, ‚ÄúVery truly I tell you, no one can enter the kingdom of God unless they are born of water and the Spirit.''
''Therefore go and make disciples of all nations, baptizing them in the name of the Father and of the Son and of the Holy Spirit'' (Matthew 28:19)
''Those who accepted his message were baptized, and about three thousand were added to their number that day.'' (Acts 2:41)
''And this water symbolizes the baptism that now saves you also - not the removal of dirt from the body, 
but the pledge of a clear conscience toward God - through the resurrection of Jesus Christ,'' (1 Peter 3:21)
''We were therefore buried with him through baptism into death in order that, 
just as Christ was raised from the dead through the glory of the Father, we too may live a new life.'' (Romans 6:4)
''Having been buried with him in baptism, in which you were also raised with him through your faith in the working of God, 
who raised him from the dead.'' (Colossians 2:12)


Please get right with God and start your relationship with Jesus Christ today before it‚Äôs too late, because there‚Äôs not much time left! 
"But about that day or hour no one knows, not even the angels in heaven, nor the Son, but only the Father.‚Äô‚Äô (Mark 13:32)
Get to know Christ through God's Word - Bible. At first I recommend reading Gospel of John and book of Romans. God bless you!

text:
I just looked it up. The average wage is 6'000.- CHF per month (around 6300.- dollars gross. That's around 5000.- dollars gross NET)
Yearly income taxes depend on the city you live in, but they are around 10-15% of your income. This you will pay additional.
It's mandatory to have a health insurance which costs you around 350.- to 450.- CHF per month. A 2 room rental apartment will cost you around 1200.- to 1800.- CHF per Mont.
Just to put it a little bit in perspective... (and don't forget average means half of the people are below it)

Have a great day! üôè And let us know if you come back to Switzerland one day. Then we can show you great things and places in Switzerland that are less expensive. ‚ò∫

text:
This claim is unbeatable! Turkey is truly the most beautiful country in the world. It showcases the most inspiring cultural treasures and stunning scenery you won't find anywhere else in the world.
Turkey's culture, history and cuisine are abundant. 81 provinces have their own local dishes, desserts and traditional dances. This makes Turkey a very popular tourist destination for people from all over the world. Turkey has a diverse landscape suitable for all types of travellers; There are snow-covered hills, plateaus, valleys, canyons, fairy chimneys, Kackar mountains, various endemic plant species and sparkling beaches. Not to mention beautiful cities like Istanbul, Antalya, Cappadocia and Rize. There are 84 UNESCO World Heritage sites throughout the country that showcase the best of Turkish history. 2 of the 7 wonders of the world are located in these lands. Turkey is a country that lives in 4 seasons. It is the country with the most climate and plant diversity because it is located on 3 continents and surrounded by seas on 3 sides. Both Tropical and Scandinavian climates occur. While there are 12,000 plant species in all of Europe, there are 9,000 plant species in Turkey alone. It is the 7th richest country in the world in terms of underground resources.  The people are hospitable and friendly. It is the country that provides the most net and humanitarian aid. Too many things to count... What you love: ‚ÄúTurkey has everything! It's the most complete country on earth‚Äù Anatolia offers a unique blend of East and West. Turkey is truly the center of the world!

3/1 of the 9,000 plant species found in Turkey are endemic. Agriculture first started in Anatolia. Europe's agricultural leader. Turkey is the first in the world in hazelnut, cherry, fig, apricot, quince and poppy production. second in the production of melon, watermelon, cherry, cucumber, carob, chickpea. mandarin, third in apple production. It ranks fourth in the production of pistachios, strawberries, chestnuts, walnuts and lentils. Tomatoes and eggplants are the main exports.

Many of the best views are found in the Black Sea, such as the fairy chimneys and rock pillars of Cappadocia or the steep peaks and alpine meadows of the Ka√ßkar Mountains. In the Aegean region, Pamukkale's frozen waterfalls and stacked pools ensure that you will never be satisfied with your hotel's infinity pool again. The Turquoise Coast (or Turkish Riviera) is another prime destination, especially if excellent beaches, mountain views, and a Mediterranean climate are what you're looking for

text:
The wife and I had been to Switzerland a couple of years ago and our experience was far less than perfect. 
It is undoubtedly a beautiful place but our interaction with the locals took away from experiencing it. We found the locals to be cold, distant, and at times downright racists.
The discriminatory treatment was so blatant that I had to look it up (while on trip) to see if we were the only ones to feel that way, and we're not. The internet is filled with accounts of expats and tourists recounting exactly what we experienced. Sadly, all of these get lost in the blogs and vlogs talking about the instagram-worthy locations and the high standards of living. 
Switzerland has a long way to go before it can claim to even be on par with other countries in the developed world in terms of acceptance and inclusion. Switzerland is not a place for people of colour and I don't think we would go back again.

text:
¬†@inaceleste5604¬† In the 2021 Mercer Cost of Living City Ranking, Zurich in Switzerland is ranked as the 5th highest COST city world-wide, while Oslo is only listed as the 55th most expensive city worldwide. So looking purely at cost, I think Norway is actually also very expensive, but Switzerland is MORE expoensive than Norway as a general statement. 

HOWEVER, for those few who are actually interested in the WHOLE picture, rather than just in one side of an equation with multiple variables, the following fact changes the COST discussion considerably: the 2021 Allianz Global Wealth Report shows Switzerland to have the 2nd highest NET assets per capita in the world together with a high GINI coefficient (0.78), which means not only are the net assets the highest per capita world-wide, but at the same time that wealth is widely distributed in the population, not concentrated in the hands of a few mega-rich, like in most eastern, middle-eastern or central european countries, where dictators, oligarchs and autocrats bilk their fiefdoms. In this same ranking, Norway has a similarly high Gini coefficient (0.72) and is listed as 24th in the world, but the net assets a norwegian has accumulated on average is only 12.7% (!) of what a typical Swiss will have accumulated at the same point in time. Keep in mind that in Switzerland, now 12% of the population (not just earners, but POPULATION, which is all the more mind-boggling) are millionaires. Only the USA with its pension funds and 401Ks invested in tech giants is comparable.

So the COST of living is just one metric. It is only one side of the equation. The answer lies in where an individual can accumulate more wealth, because to accumulate more wealth automatically means there is a larger positive delta between what the typical average person spends in total and what he/she can save in total.  And imho, THAT's what constitutes actual "cost of living". It should probably be called "NET cost of living". And by that metric, for People living and earning their incomes in Switzerland, Switzerland is actually one of the lowest "NET cost countries" in the world, since people can accumulate by FAR the most in the world.

text:
¬†@christheswiss390¬†
Thank you for your extensive answer. I've been to Iceland, I'm an immigrant in Norway so I know what you mean about the wealth distribution in other parts of the world.

The last two years I had traveled to Lofoten, Norway and I want to visit Switzerland. Any recommendations for places with a similar landscape? I was thinking taking a train ride, that's one on my bucket list.. How about a hike with amazing views fit for non-sporty gal like me? üòú
author: @inaceleste5604

text:
¬†@inaceleste5604¬† Hi Ina

As the Lofotens are an island group in the ocean, it will be hard to find the comparable landscape in Switzerland. üòâ

But considering mountainous and picturistique regions, I would recommend the Bernese alps (central Switzerland), The Vallais (southwestern Switzerland IN the alps) and the Engiadina (Eastern Switzerland) with its gorgeous national park.
As tourists very often visit unnnaturally high elevations in Switzerland, It's best to be dressed WARMLY.

I would recommend going to the "top of Europe" on the Jungfrau Joch from Grindelwald. It's a famous train ride, but at the top you can actually exit and hike along a wide and easy snow field for about 1.5 hours to a small alpine hut and restaurant, or just turn around and head back whenever you feel like it.
 
Also, You could take the funiculars up to the First from Grindelwald and do some easier hikes up there and even take a cart or bicycle back down the mountain on nice, well prepared paths to Grindelwald again.

IN the Valais, you should go to the Aletsch arena, take the funiculars to the top and then do a bit of walking to see the Aletsch glacier - the largest in continental Europe.

In Engiadina you could walk to the Morteratsch glacier - only approx 1 hour and only slightly up-hill and VERY beautiful. Plus, take the cable car up to Muotas-Muragl (near St. Moritz) and you can do some nice hiking up there. Plus, take the funicular up the Diavolezza and you can hike up there as well. Stunning scenery included. Then take the Train across the Bernina pass and get off at the alp Gr√ºm, the scenery will leave you speechless again.
Then take a train to Zernez, hop on the postal bus (it's like the Hurtigrouten, but it's buses for Swiss mountains), ride into the national park and do one or two easier hikes there. Go to the visitor center in Zernez firt to get information, maps, even borrow binoculars, etc
And by all means - enjoy the trip SOLEY by train. You can even have the Swiss Railways take care of your luggage and have it picked up at the hotel and delivered to the next hotel with minimal fuss or expenses.

¬†@aamirrazak3467¬†Lucerne is actually the most beautiful city (Bern and Solothurn, Schaffhausen and Stein am Rhein are nice, too, though).
There is a super touristy part where accommodation is rather luxurious and expensive but like 500m (because it's a small place) away from that super touristy spot you'll find cheaper accommodation, especially air b'n'b or simple old school b'n'b, also you'll find yourself in the middle of Switzerland and everything beautiful and interesting (German and Italian part) is roughly 100km in any direction. 
You can hop on a train "the Voralpenexpress" and travel to Lake Constance in one day and back and have the most beautiful Alpine crossing view.
The next day you hop on a train and visit Bern and so on.
Also the night life is great in Lucerne. You'll find everything you want here and very nice metropolitan people in a rather small, but immensely beautiful city.

Lived there as an American for about 5 years as a businessman. It was both the best of times and the strangest of times, but it is most certainly not the best place. Yes, beautiful mountains and lakes, but read on‚Ä¶

Not just crazy expensive, but very strange people and very insular, aka racist about ANYONE who is not Swiss or cannot speak the local language or was not in the Swiss army with them. My wife happens to be Asian, and 2 co-workers told me directly that in Switzerland, Asian woman are all thought to be prostitutes‚Ä¶.thought they were kidding, but not. Then anyone recall the ugliness around Swiss Nazi gold?? Swiss citizens also think they are all part of the secret police, so expect random people to tell you everything you are doing wrong at all times from not crossing at a crosswalk, to not looking deeply into each other‚Äôs eyes while doing cheers over a glass of wine, and on and on. 

Sadly, not the enchanted country that they would like to portray. I did love the whole Swiss experience, but dont think for a minute that it was all wonderful fondue, chocolates and views.

text:
It really depends on WHAT you are seeking, I've been over to Switzerland since 2013-ish nearly every year for the Genvea motorshow, but I also get to explore/live a local life for a short period. Now, I wouldn't call it perfect,  they still have the same issues (disparity of wealth, drugs, etc) as any other country. Its seems to be a place that gets "blown-up" a lot owing to its unique geological postion in the world, which I get, because when I popped over a large hill near Lausanne in a Range Rover (L405), to then see the Alps, it took my breath away (the heated and massage seats helped ;) ).

I was born in South London, UK, and now live not too far from Oxford (or Hogwarts as some people might know it as), I would say that I already live in one the best countries in the world. One of the best countries, not the best,  the best country doesn't exist.

text:
Being born in Bern (1966) and living in B√ºren I see people that truly care for their country.

In that entire I did not see one piece of garbage, those bikes sitting outside at the bike shop would‚Äôve been gone here in the states, the public espresso machine would be broken/vandalized and I honestly can‚Äôt see any adventure company in the states allowing their clients to repel down to the river.

As far as cost, I can‚Äôt tell you how many times here that I‚Äôve made the comment ‚ÄúI‚Äôll pay more for higher quality‚Äù not only in restaurants, but grocery stores, hotels cleanliness, or any business you have to do business with.

My uncle and his family live in Grenchen who I try to keep in contact with several times during the year, and the one thing that I really find interesting about Switzerland is that school kids are not taught the ‚Äúyou must go to college‚Äù mentality and given the choice of high quality blue collar careers.  My uncle‚Äôs daughter recently quit her waitress job that she was required to internship for four years, and now she gave it up due to late nights and weekend work (almost unheard of in Switzerland) so now she is starting a four year internship on autobody/paint work. His son is currently in a internship to drive trucks cross country. Until very recent years those carriers in the states are overlooked due to low pay and negative stigma behind them, but now with most young adults going to college it has left a huge gap in blue collar expertise. Most young adults would never look at being an electrician, plumber, or in my case custom cabinet maker, but up here in the western Washington area (Seattle, Kirkland, Bellevue, Issaquah, etc) with all of the Tech employers these kids are paying huge money for simple tasks. Several weeks ago there was a news story on this situation and they just happened to do a story of a Seattle area plumbing company where the owner stated that he needs to hire 5 plumbers. He stated that he is willing to pay $20 an hour to go through his training class for 6 months and then stated that he has 5 plumbers currently working for him making over $200k.

text: We always spend about 2 months in Europe every summer, visiting different countries/cities. We took the Bernina train from Italy to St Moritz, Switzerland. The train ride was amazing and gorgeous. Highland recommend. We stayed at the biggest hotel I‚Äôve ever seen in my life, Grand Hotel Kepinksi (reminded me of the hotel from the Shining).  Believe me, Switzerland is SUPER EXPENSIVE. We had 3 kids with us and every single meal was over $200, even for just a kids spaghetti and burgers lunch. It was more expensive than Iceland, Singapore, New York, Paris, etc. But it was also beautiful and breath taking. We took the lift up the mountain and hiked down. It was like The Sound of Music. There were cows, meadows, snow capped peaks, and beautiful blue lakes.

text:
Switzerland is pretty far from being the most perfect country on the planet. Me and many of my friends have moved out or are moving out of this country. It is slow, grey, people are distant and grumpy, but the air quality is nice indeed.
Even as a young adult you feel like you are retired in this country (it is comfortable and not in the best way possible). The few friends I know that want to stay there will live their regular 9-5 job for the rest of their life and go have a few beers at the regular bar at the end of the week (wich sounds pretty similar to an average normal life anywhere in the world, except that you might have a better appartement and drinkable tap water). But these friends have not travelled too much, I am still convinced that If they traveled more, they would definitly want to move out of swizerland and chase the multi-colored life experience. 

You would think that most of the swiss live a super comfy and wealthy lifestyle too, right? wrong.
When I was a young student, I was doing a door to door job on the side, so I've met many many people in many places in switzerland. Many of them were really struggling with bills, they feel like they either have to catch up or to take get ahead financially to pay everything. Everything revolves around money, you HAVE to make a lot because you're going to spend a lot.

text:
Switzerland! Neutral...Baahhh

(BBC) For decades, US and German intelligence used this Swiss company's encoding devices to spy on other countries, and the revelations this week have provoked outrage. From the Cold War into the 2000s, Crypto AG sold the devices to more than 120 governments worldwide. The machines were encrypted but it emerged this week that the CIA and Germany's BND had rigged the devices so they could crack the codes and intercept thousands of messages. Nazi Germany found a safe place for its looted art and gold in Swiss banks. It sent trains full of weapons across Switzerland to support Italian dictator Benito Mussolini. The history books were rewritten to include the shameful policy of turning Jewish refugees back at the borders. Commissions of inquiry were set up, memorials held, and a Swiss government minister, Kaspar Villiger, formally apologised. That's the same Kaspar Villiger who now stands accused, while serving as defence minister in the 1990s, of knowing that the CIA controlled Crypto AG, and was selling flawed encryption machines around the world in order to spy on foreign governments. - SO Switzerland neutral, bahhh, in reality a cover to exploit all! - How on earth can those two concepts - neutrality and cooperation - exist together? Perhaps in the same way that Switzerland proudly does not fight wars, but sells plenty of weapons. Or the way in which its bankers used to say "money doesn't smell". In other words, they were happy to look after it whatever bloody conflict, brutal dictator, drug baron, or tax scam it had come from. Every few years it seems the Swiss get a wake-up call about their neutrality. They have to learn all over again that it's not a shining beacon of hope at the heart of Europe. And sometimes, as with Crypto AG, that pragmatism, together with a desire to see the myth of neutrality rather than the reality, leads to some very questionable decisions.

Nestl√©. Maggi noodles
In May 2015, Food Safety Regulators from the state of Uttar Pradesh, India, found that samples of Nestl√© India's Maggi noodles had up to 17 times more than the permissible safe amount of lead, in addition to monosodium glutamate. Due to this, on 3 June 2015, the New Delhi Government banned the sale of Maggi in New Delhi stores for 15 days. Some of India's biggest retailers, such as Future Group, Big Bazaar, Easyday, and Nilgiris, had imposed a nationwide ban on Maggi as of 3 June 2015. On 4 June 2015, the Gujarat FD banned the sale of the noodles for 30 days after 27 out of 39 samples were detected with objectionable levels of metallic lead, among other things. On 5 June 2015, Food Safety and Standards Authority of India (FSSAI) orders banned all nine approved variants of Maggi instant noodles from India, deeming them "unsafe and hazardous" for human consumption,and Nepal indefinitely banned Maggi over concerns about lead levels in the product. Also on 5 June, the Food Standards Agency of the United Kingdom launched an investigation to test levels of lead in Maggi. Maggi noodles have been withdrawn in five African nations ‚Äì Kenya, Uganda, Tanzania, Rwanda, and South Sudan ‚Äì by a supermarket chain after a complaint by the Consumer Federation of Kenya. 
As of August 2015, India's government made public that it was seeking damages of nearly $100 million from Nestl√© India for "unfair trade practices" following the June ban on Maggi noodles. The 6.4 billion rupee (approximately US$93 million) suit was filed with the National Consumer Disputes Redressal Commission (NCDRC), regarded as the country's top consumer court, but was settled on 13 August 2015. 

In the Philippines, localized versions of Maggi instant noodles were sold until 2011 when the product group was recalled for suspected salmonella contamination. The product did not return to market.

(Wiki)
Glencore in Ecuador
"In Ecuador, the current government has tried to reduce the role played by middlemen such as Glencore with state oil company Petroecuador" due to questions about transparency and follow-through, according to Fernando Villavicencio, a Quito-based oil sector analyst.
Glencore in Zambia
According to a Reuters article in 2011 ‚ÄúOfficials in Zambia believe pollution from Glencore's Mopani mine is causing acid rain and health problems in an area where 5 million people live. The emissions were reported to exceed the WHO-recommendations by a factor of 70 up to 2013.The emissions now exceed the recommendations by 3% of 70 = 210%.
In January 2019, a delegation from the Federal Department of Foreign Affairs under the leadership of Ignazio Cassis made a controversial visit to the Mopani Copper Mines that also produce cobalt ores. The Swiss government had previously issued human rights guidelines for firms operating in the commodity sector, which is of strategic importance to both countries. The visit was heavily criticized by Amnesty International and Swiss watchdog groups while the federal councilor defended his stance. 
Investments in Brazil
In June 2018 Glencore purchased a 78% stake in Ale Combust√≠veis S.A., a Brazilian fuel distribution company. Through Ale Glencore aimed to expand its fuel distribution network by forging agreements with unbranded gas stations.

(Wiki)
Glencore. Democratic Republic of the Congo
The company's Luilu copper refinery uses acid to extract the copper. For three years after taking over the mine, it continued to allow the waste acid to flow into a river. The chief executive, Ivan Glasenberg, was interviewed for Panorama by John Sweeney and said 'It was impossible to remedy any way faster. Glencore said the pollution started long before the company took over the refinery and that it has now ended. A reporter for The Guardian found children as young as ten years underground at the Tilwezembe mine, which the company had said in a 2008 prospectus that it had closed due to falling copper prices. CEO Glasenberg said the company does not profit from child labor, and the child miners went with artisanal mining by nearby residents that Glencore was trying to prevent. But (BBC¬¥s) Panorama tracked a shipment of copper from the mine to Groupe Bazano plant and from that plant to a Glencore smelter in Zambia.
Glencore was also accused of acquiring illicit "conflict minerals" In a detailed letter sent to Global Witness, the company denied any wrongdoing.
Glencore acquired stakes in the Kansuki mine in Congo's southern Katanga Province in 2012. According to Global Witness, Congo's government transferred a 75% stake in Kansuki mine in secret and at vastly undervalued prices in July 2010 to a company in which Dan Gertler, who is a close friend of President Joseph Kabila, has an interest. Just a month later, in August 2010, Glencore took half the shares of the company that acquired that 75% stake, becoming the operator of the mine. Glencore is financing the entire development of the Kansuki mine, thereby carrying the costs for the other partner companies, which are associated with Mr. Gertler. Glencore said at the time "During the period when these transactions took place, Glencore had decided in general not to increase its shareholdings in DRC projects."
Glencore acquired a 50% share in SAMREF Congo SPRL in 2007, a Congolese-registered company holding 80% of the Mutanda Mine. According to Global Witness, SAMREF recommended on 1 March 2011 that Congo's state-run company G√©camines, holding the other 20% of the Mutanda Mine, sell this share to an entity also associated with Dan Gertler and went on to question the links between Glencore and Dan Gertler. Glencore has been designated operator of the Mutanda Mine. Glencore has responded a number of times to Global Witness regarding these allegations.

My basic bucket list is definitely Italy, Greece, Spain, France, Switzerland, Austria, Iceland, Australia, Mozambique, Indonesia and Philippines. Let me know if which one out of this list I should definitely bump up to the top. Places I would be less keen on would probably be most Islamic law countries, warring countries, India, and some Central African countries.
Out of curiosity, why was Egypt your least favourite?
author: @Carolina-rd3gh

text:
¬†@Carolina-rd3gh¬† thanks for sharing your opinions: Regarding with your choice of countries, I can tell you the following:

1.Switzerland - it should be on your top if you like beautiful landscapes, very safe, very clean and nice people. Plus, you can easily visit Italy, France and Austria since they very close to each other. This is my top country of all.

2. Spain - very friendly people and cheaper than Switzerland and it is not so cold too. lived there for 3 months

3. Italy and France - they are nice, more to offer but people do not really speak english. Italy has better food.

3. Greece - because of the beaches and their architectures. My husband and I will be in Greece this summer.

4. Indonesia - nice people, good food and beautiful beaches, although most of them are muslim. Traffic is bit pain the butt.

5. Philippines - my home country. Please do not really stay in the big city coz it is not really safe, not so many diverse food and a bit pricy BUT beautiful beaches. Try to look for Boracay, El Nido, Palawan, Coron. Most people speak English and very friendly too.

6. Austrialia - nice landscapes and beaches but expensive

7. Iceland - very cold but beautiful. Never been there yet, but will try to visit this year or next year to see the aurora borealis(my bucket list)

Recommendations:

1. Thailand - my second home(10 years living there), easy, cheap, nice people, one of the best country when it comes to great food. My husband loves Thailand, so much!

2. New Zealand and Canada - beautiful landscapes

3. Slovenia - it is like Switzerland but cheaper than Switzerland. We will visit this place next week and to see Lake Bled

4. Maldives - beautiful beaches 


I haven't been to Mozambique, so cannot really tell and no plans to go there. I would like to go to Tanzania or Seychelles.
Egypt was my least country to visit because I was being mistreated by men together with police when me and my husband were walking along the road when we were in Cairo to visit the Giza.

text:
Reality from Switzerland, as reported by the press, part 3

It is human to make mistakes, it is inhuman not to try to prevent repeating mistakes made....

(BBC) 
For decades, US and German intelligence used this Swiss company's encoding devices to spy on other countries, and the revelations this week have provoked outrage. From the Cold War into the 2000s, Crypto AG sold the devices to more than 120 governments worldwide. The machines were encrypted but it emerged this week that the CIA and Germany's BND had rigged the devices so they could crack the codes and intercept thousands of messages. Nazi Germany found a safe place for its looted art and gold in Swiss banks. It sent trains full of weapons across Switzerland to support Italian dictator Benito Mussolini. The history books were rewritten to include the shameful policy of turning Jewish refugees back at the borders. Commissions of inquiry were set up, memorials held, and a Swiss government minister, Kaspar Villiger, formally apologised. That's the same Kaspar Villiger who now stands accused, while serving as defence minister in the 1990s, of knowing that the CIA controlled Crypto AG, and was selling flawed encryption machines around the world in order to spy on foreign governments. - SO Switzerland neutral, bahhh, in reality a cover to exploit all! - How on earth can those two concepts - neutrality and cooperation - exist together? Perhaps in the same way that Switzerland proudly does not fight wars, but sells plenty of weapons. Or the way in which its bankers used to say "money doesn't smell". In other words, they were happy to look after it whatever bloody conflict, brutal dictator, drug baron, or tax scam it had come from. Every few years it seems the Swiss get a wake-up call about their neutrality. They have to learn all over again that it's not a shining beacon of hope at the heart of Europe. And sometimes, as with Crypto AG, that pragmatism, together with a desire to see the myth of neutrality rather than the reality, leads to some very questionable decisions.

(NDTV)
Police raided UEFA's offices in Geneva as part of a probe into a Champions League television rights deal signed by Gianni Infantino before he became FIFA president.

(Reuters)
A risk management failure in the initial lines of defense protecting Credit Suisse was identified as the root cause of losses linked to Archegos, with senior management ignorant of the bank's exposure to the hedge fund all the way up to its collapse

(ABC)

In 2005, proceeds from an oil sale to Glencore were seized as fraudulent gains as part of an investigation into corruption in the Democratic Republic of Congo.

(Wiki)
Glencore DRC and China
In March 2018, it was reported that Glencore would sell one third (13,800 tonnes) of its cobalt output to China's battery recycler GEM. 18,000 tonnes are to be sold in 2019, and 21,000 in 2020. During the FT Commodities Global Summit in Lausanne, Switzerland, CEO Glasenberg stated "if cobalt falls into the hands of the Chinese, yeah you won‚Äôt see EVs being produced in Europe etc." Yet, Glasenberg then said that he was prepared to sell DRC cobalt mines to China if the price was good. Concurrently, a Chinese take-over of some of the mines became a real possibility due to a legal dispute about royalty payments to Gertler and G√©camines.The DRC supplies 60% of the world's cobalt ore, while China produces more than 80% of the world‚Äôs refined cobalt

Trafigura. Wastedumping in C√¥te d'Ivoire

The 2006 C√¥te d'Ivoire toxic waste dump was a health crisis in C√¥te d'Ivoire in which the Probo Koala, a ship registered in Panama and chartered by Trafigura, hired a local contractor to offload waste in Abidjan after refusing to pay a ‚Ç¨1,000 per cubic metre surcharge imposed by Amsterdam Port Services to discourage waste disposal in the Netherlands. The local contractor, Tommy, improperly dumped the waste materials at as many as 12 sites in and around the city of Abidjan in August 2006. The gas caused by the release of these chemicals is blamed by the UN and the government of C√¥te d'Ivoire for the deaths of 17 and the injury of over 30,000 Ivorians, with injuries that ranged from mild headaches to severe burns of skin and lungs. Almost 100,000 Ivorians sought medical attention.  
Trafigura maintains that the substance dumped consisted of "slops", or waste water from washing the Probo Koala's tanks. An inquiry in the Netherlands, in late 2006, confirmed the substance to consist of more than 500 tonnes of a mix of fuel, hydrogen sulfide, and sodium hydroxide, known as caustic soda.
Trafigura denied any waste was transported from the Netherlands, saying that the substances contained only tiny amounts of hydrogen sulfide, and that the company did not know the substance was to be disposed of improperly. Trafigura officials, including Claude Dauphin and the company‚Äôs West Africa regional director, traveled to Abidjan to assist in the cleanup effort but were arrested and imprisoned by the Ivorian government. While its executives were being held, the company agreed to pay US$198 million for cleanup to the Ivorian government without admitting wrongdoing, and the Ivorian government pledged not to prosecute the company.[Dauphin and his fellow executives were released following the settlement.
In 2008 a civil lawsuit in London was launched by almost 30,000 Ivorians against Trafigura. In May 2009 Trafigura announced it would sue the BBC for libel after its Newsnight program alleged the company had knowingly sought to cover up its role in the incident. In September 2009 The Guardian obtained and published internal Trafigura emails showing that the traders responsible knew how dangerous the chemicals were. Shortly afterwards Trafigura agreed to a settlement of ¬£30 million (US$42.4 million) to settle the suit.[In 2010 a Dutch court found Trafigura guilty of illegally exporting toxic waste from Amsterdam.

text: It's sad to read the high prices are the only thing you mention that you remember about your Switzerland tour. But yes, coming from less afluent countries makes Swiss prices seem sky high. When Swiss make the appropriate salary in their country, not only can they afford those sky-high prices and STILL save many tens of thousands every year and create personal wealth , but they can actually travel the whole world on their ample, 5 weeks of annual paid vacations and every single country they visit is cheaper than at home. Also, when a Swiss retires, he / she can actually choose which country in the world he / she wants to go live in (or stay in Switzerland) and easily live there like a king / queen off the pension income, since all other countries are far "cheaper". So there are two sides to the "expensive" Swiss holidays topic. For foreign travelers that can't really afford it, Switzerland can be tough to travel. But for the Swiss, it's a sign their economy is strong, their currency is rock-solid and they can afford to travel anywhere on the globe (and thy DO!) or retire anywhere in the world they want. Not to forget: the Swiss also happen to have one of the highest life-expectencies in the world, so they also have many more years to enjoy their wealth than others. When you're fortunate enough or have the foresight to become part of that successful society, it's a pretty sweet deal.

text:
¬†@Aiibh¬† Haha, I know what you mean. üòÇ

Nobody is asking anybody to praise high prices. That would be cruel. üòÇ 

I'm not even criticising the discussion of high prices. What I AM saying is that prices in Paris, London or any number of other tourist hot spots are just as high and in fact even higher, considering the low salaries the locals are making vs the Swiss salaries. Yet because it's those large cities, everybody just seems to assume that's normal. But when they travel to a tourist hot spot out in the Swiss countryside, THEN all of a sudden everyone's up in arms about the high prices. That's just illogical, irrational and a bit hypocritical.

What I am also saying is that since almost all countries in the world are less affluent, for most of their citizens Switzerland is an unaffordable travel destination. BUt most tourists travel to Switzerland anyway, despite KNOWING damn well that Switzerland is prohibitively exepnsive for them. Perhaps there is also an unspoken desire to "prove" to themselves and their family and friends that they CAN afford it - perhaps there is even a bit of showing off going on, and the pain of REAL sticker shock then gets "vented" in forums and on platforms such as YT. Again - that behaviour is hypocritical, since I'm strongly assuming the world by now has understood that one of the wealthiest nations in the world is also one of the most expensive countries in the world, don't you think?

Forward lookking: as the Swiss Franc continues to appreciate against all major currencies and will do so for the foreseeable future (as it has also done for the past 50 years!), it stands to reason that experiencing Switzerland will in fact get even (much!) MORE expensive in the coming years for non-Swiss travellers. This is a good thing, as it will entice more budget-minded tourists to focus on more affordable destinations (the world is FULL of those) and limit the Swiss holiday to a smaller, but much more appreciative and less price-sensitive, more unique experience seeking clientel, imho. No more sticker shock for low-cost discount seekers, no more overrun tourist hotspots, less waiting in line for the tourists and less traffic for the Swiss. Win - win - win - win!  üòâ

text:
¬†@Aiibh¬† I think we all have places we deem "worth it" and places we feel are too expensive or "not worth it", and that's very personal and how it should be. I hope you DO feel Switz was worth it and DO have a second (and third and fourth) chance. Your approach and clarity of stance deserve kudos.

Actually, I hope some day you'll be in a position to do what quite a few people (that I personally know) from abroad do: they go on holidays to the same place in Switzerland since many years - some since decades. Some even have their chauffeurs drive their cars from Spain, France, Germany or the UK (right hand drive so the wife is used to it) to Switz. with all the luggage, skis and stuff, then the family flies in on a PJ, stays a few weeks; mom or dad might fly home for the occasional business meeting and then return for more fun 'n sun. The kids have their friends since years that also stay at the same places and hotels, they are out skiing all day with their friends (sans parents), then out partying every night on their own (something hors question at their native domicile due to safety restrictions), but the parents know its safe in the small towns in Switzerland, no one is worried, the parents are also out partying with THEIR friends from all over the world they've accumulated in the same hot spot over the years, and when they leave, the entire family is already dreaming of the next vacation. I hope you can do THAT kind of travel some day!

Two things to consider here:
1. imagine how much such a family spends in Switzerland in just 2 x 3 weeks, every year (x-mas and February). Now imagine how many families from abroad do this every year in the hotspots in Switzerland, once they've realized that entire value proposition not openly advertized but very real. Perhaps 15 to 20 thousand families in the entire small country? And they consider EVERY PENNY spent totally worth it. They would spend even more if they had to and still wouldn't bat an eye.
2. Imagine how much that safety of knowing your kids are out partying with the kids of people you've known for years and that are just as paranoid about safety as you and knowing there is no kidnapping, no violence, no harassment, no paperazzi, no tabloids, nothing to worry about, and your kids AND you are just letting loose and REALLY enjoying life for a few weeks each year. The value proposition of that peace of mind: Priceless.

To those people, Switzerland is a solidly CHEAP place, considering they get value no money in the world could buy them anywhere else. Crazy world, right?

author: @TimonSauter

text:
¬†@bearinch¬† I'm a person that likes real, actual data, as opposed to what "someone heard".

Fact: in the 1980s, Switzerland had 4.7 million inhabitants. in 2020, they had "grown" to 8.5 million (approx. +85%!!). If you can tell me which other highly desirable country has experienced the same "growth" (influx of foreigners) while STILL maintaining the same level of well-being, job-security, affluence, building of top-notch infrastructure for an almost doubled people, comparatively high pension payouts and life expectancy (so that rules out SH countries), I'll gladly concede your point. Until then, I'll just stick with my view that a few 10,000 people leaving Switzerland is a good sign for Switzerland. Unfortunately, the influx of foreigners is still higher than the outflux (which is why the country has grown more than almost any other country in Europe over the past 40 -50 years).

Most of the older people leaving Switzerland do so because their  pension pay-out from Switzerland allows them to live like kings in much poorer countries, which applies to almost all countries you compare Switzerland to. THIS is the main driver for leaving Switzerland after so many years - and it is absolutely a viable driver. I'm assuming most of the people you are referring to are of similar age and have the "unspoken retirement benefits of the high Swiss Franc". However, most people just won't admit this is a major factor in their decision process, as it also means they are actually benefitting off the lower income level of the "new" country of residence. Honesty is a rare commodity on public platforms...

Regarding "A lot of quite wired things going on here" (you win the prize for being vague): all countries I know change massively over time. I know many Australians that are horrified how their previously freedom oriented country has become a left-wing, woke, cover-your-ass compliant, super nanny state and very legally obsessed - they often flee again after just a few months there. Same for Americans, which often return to a dysfunctional police state. I don't even want to START with Italians, Greeks or Portuguese who have gotten used to doctors in Switzerland that don't need bribing for service and hospitals where you actually get real food rather than having to bring your own and trains that actually show up on schedule. So I'm crossing my fingers for you - good luck!

text:
I can relate, Leo!   This is how I look at it:
Many places in Switzerland are a bit like nice towns in northern Europe,  places like Connecticut and wealthy American towns by the sea. It's a seemingly perfect little paradise with an illusion of promising eternal bliss. When you live there, however, your soul will slowly melt away under the rigid and oppressive social structures and norms. It's probably the least free place despite the clean streets, big skies, and open views. You can only pursue what makes you happy in a quiet corner where you won't stir up to much dust or draw attention to yourself. No nail is allowed to stick out too far and if it does it will get beaten back down to the level of the others. I grew up in one of these places. There is no celebration of diversity and difference. What is celebrated is the maintenance of "normal", of "tradition", "conservation". Which makes it a nice place to visit as it has been able to maintain a sterile functional society. However, this comes at the expense of a more human experience that one can only find in places that are a bit more chaotic and alive.

It's really not the perfect country at all. If you think it is then here are some points you might want to think about:
- Mandatory pension that you cannot opt out of

- The dating market is a complete mess. If you're not a 6'3 rich handsome chad then you don't stand a chance at getting anything at all.

- Government control is very prominent when it comes to medical status and very controlling. Many people cannot even go into a restaurant or to their gym now
- When a child is born if you're a man you must claim parternity by signing a contract with the government to pay child support whether married or not and if they dont like it then you have no rights as a father
- Switzerland pretends to be conservative and tax efficient but it's really not. Cantons vary but you can easily expect to pay 20%+ in taxes from your gross income.
marriage in switzerland is a nightmare the family courts are very matriarchal. 95% of alimoney and child support goes to women causing a huge rise in male suicide rates. the divorce rates in switzerland are absolutely huge with most of the wealth transfer going to women and child custody going to women automatically.
I could go on all day
IT IS NOT PERFECT. NOT EVEN CLOSE.

text:
Nice video! It was very fun to watch. It's interesting to see how American tourists experience Switzerland. Just please chill on the fake facts, it gives our country a non-realistic image.  

1) Why would you drive? Trains and busses go absolutely everywhere and a month-long all enabling train-bus-boat pass is 250 CHF, much cheaper than a rental car which is over taxed for a reason. Also trains are faster than cars.

2) The "highest point in Europe" thing is a marketing thing, it's not actually the highest point, which would be the top of the mont blanc üòÖ. Also prices are only that over expensive in and around Interlaken which is a tourist trap city (but is very beautiful to visit). For example, you can stay in a nice hotel in the center of Zurich (which is a very fancy city) for about 100.-/night. Also fondue in a restaurant is usually like 20.- not 65 üòÇ. 

3) The average salary here is more like 60kchf and not 125k lol, and only a few cantons actually have minimum wage, it's not a federal thing.

Not trying to bash or anything, I actually enjoyed the video, just correcting a few of the exaggerations.

text:
If you're ever here, perhaps consider taking one or two Postauto tours. The advantage with them is, some go places you'd never think of, and everybody's free to soak up the scenery because a professional driver is at the wheel. And you get to walk around in the bus. They're public buses that run on a schedule, some go through an amazing scenery. Unfortunately, the really interesting lines aren't serviced all year, some only as short as June through October, until the first serious snowfalls.

In the Berner Oberland, which is the area this clip was filmed in, and since they had partially bad weather, Line 682 might have been an option. While there are shortcuts, the full roundtrip across four mountainpasses takes 8 3/4 hours, start and end are in Meiringen (just a few kilometers east of where the spent their nights, maybe 10 miles).

Another interesting one, with up to 28% ascent/descent the steepest line in Switzerland, leaves Reichenbach for Griesalp. 

And of course there's lots more.

text: Considering the size of the US and what kind of roadtrips you take just for a fun evening out ( lets hit vegas tonight !(from LA)) you can absolutely call Switzerland a big amusement park. You can enter it in the north, from germany, speaking german, cloudy/rainy weather, 60ish¬∞, and start going south, and once you drive through the Gotthard tunnel, a 10mile tunnel going under the main alps, you come out in the italian speaking part of the country, and it's suddenly blue skies and 85¬∞ and you see palms and mediterrenean vegetation. I know it's hard to grasp, but the alps are this massive geological barrier, imagine being in a blizzard in Pontiac/MI and fed up with the cold. so you hop in your car, drive for 60min and there you are, south carolina. author: @daleguerra5326

text:
¬†@daleguerra5326¬† Sure Dale ! Well, the things about racism is sadly mostly in the "outer cantons" as I call them, not a majority at all in Switzerland but it still exists, these are in every canton of course but mostly in the canton of Jura (near of where I live, I am a Berner) and Geneva.
As for the expensive things, it is for everyone. It's a fact that a lot of things are expensive in Switzerland so generally peoples would like to tap around 6k to 7k/month jobs.
Sociability issues is kind of true, outside of working actually, but actions like saying hello to random people is something common in village, school, city outskirts and suburbs. Respecting others is a part of our culture but it's generally those not directly IN the culture who might not be too sociable. The Swiss are generally very cool and chill as long as you don't ask them very deep and hard questions.

The outsiders thought is true mostly in the inside cantons, again not a majority but still, it's in my canton, Bern, Luzern, Zug the Unterwalden, Schwyz and Uri mostly.

For the bad points in my opinion is the crisis problem. As you may know Switzerland is as of 2021 a Federal Republic (Technically a Confederation), so the cantons are subject to all laws of the government aswell as the Federal Constitution which is the highest authority and has to be respected by all cantons in order to keep them united. The thing is that Switzerland is hard at handling the COVID as of now because of the federalism and the cantons having yes, a strict minimum, but aswell don't general reinforce the policies. They prefer to keep physical work disregarding the other ideas.

That's all I kind of had to say, if there are any other questions, I'll be there to answer them!

Maggi noodles In May 2015, Food Safety Regulators from the state of Uttar Pradesh, India, found that samples of Nestl√© India's Maggi noodles had up to 17 times more than the permissible safe amount of lead, in addition to monosodium glutamate. Due to this, on 3 June 2015, the New Delhi Government banned the sale of Maggi in New Delhi stores for 15 days. Some of India's biggest retailers, such as Future Group, Big Bazaar, Easyday, and Nilgiris, had imposed a nationwide ban on Maggi as of 3 June 2015. On 4 June 2015, the Gujarat FD banned the sale of the noodles for 30 days after 27 out of 39 samples were detected with objectionable levels of metallic lead, among other things. On 5 June 2015, Food Safety and Standards Authority of India (FSSAI) orders banned all nine approved variants of Maggi instant noodles from India, deeming them "unsafe and hazardous" for human consumption,and Nepal indefinitely banned Maggi over concerns about lead levels in the product. Also on 5 June, the Food Standards Agency of the United Kingdom launched an investigation to test levels of lead in Maggi. Maggi noodles have been withdrawn in five African nations ‚Äì Kenya, Uganda, Tanzania, Rwanda, and South Sudan ‚Äì by a supermarket chain after a complaint by the Consumer Federation of Kenya. As of August 2015, India's government made public that it was seeking damages of nearly $100 million from Nestl√© India for "unfair trade practices" following the June ban on Maggi noodles. The 6.4 billion rupee (approximately US$93 million) suit was filed with the National Consumer Disputes Redressal Commission (NCDRC), regarded as the country's top consumer court, but was settled on 13 August 2015. In the Philippines, localized versions of Maggi instant noodles were sold until 2011 when the product group was recalled for suspected salmonella contamination. Glencore in Democratic Republic of the Congo 
The company's Luilu copper refinery uses acid to extract the copper. For three years after taking over the mine, it continued to allow the waste acid to flow into a river. The chief executive, Ivan Glasenberg, was interviewed for Panorama by John Sweeney and said 'It was impossible to remedy any way faster. Just a month later, in August 2010, Glencore took half the shares of the company that acquired that 75% stake, becoming the operator of the mine. Glencore said at the time "During the period when these transactions took place, Glencore had decided in general not to increase its shareholdings in DRC projects." text: ‚Äã¬†@Mike-ox8sq¬† How about calming down? I do not understand why some people finger point at Switzerland enabling money laundring and other criminal activities. I will not say it doesn't happen by us. It surely does, but compared to other countries the corruption index is very low here (google corruption index: we are ranked 3rd world wide). So how about looking first at those places where corruption is highest, before screaming around saying we enable criminals to hide money? As I wrote on page 1: ‚ÄúEVERY time I receive 1 (one) negative comment on this text, I will add another page listing companies or organisations that have committed anything from murderous atrocities to corruption, market manipulation and other illegal and unethical behavior related to Switzerland‚Äù.


(Wiki)
Trafigura. Wastedumping in C√¥te d'Ivoire

The 2006 C√¥te d'Ivoire toxic waste dump was a health crisis in C√¥te d'Ivoire in which the Probo Koala, a ship registered in Panama and chartered by Trafigura, hired a local contractor to offload waste in Abidjan after refusing to pay a ‚Ç¨1,000 per cubic metre surcharge imposed by Amsterdam Port Services to discourage waste disposal in the Netherlands. The local contractor, Tommy, improperly dumped the waste materials at as many as 12 sites in and around the city of Abidjan in August 2006. The gas caused by the release of these chemicals is blamed by the UN and the government of C√¥te d'Ivoire for the deaths of 17 and the injury of over 30,000 Ivorians, with injuries that ranged from mild headaches to severe burns of skin and lungs. Almost 100,000 Ivorians sought medical attention.  
Trafigura maintains that the substance dumped consisted of "slops", or waste water from washing the Probo Koala's tanks. An inquiry in the Netherlands, in late 2006, confirmed the substance to consist of more than 500 tonnes of a mix of fuel, hydrogen sulfide, and sodium hydroxide, known as caustic soda.
Trafigura denied any waste was transported from the Netherlands, saying that the substances contained only tiny amounts of hydrogen sulfide, and that the company did not know the substance was to be disposed of improperly. Trafigura officials, including Claude Dauphin and the company‚Äôs West Africa regional director, traveled to Abidjan to assist in the cleanup effort but were arrested and imprisoned by the Ivorian government. While its executives were being held, the company agreed to pay US$198 million for cleanup to the Ivorian government without admitting wrongdoing, and the Ivorian government pledged not to prosecute the company.[Dauphin and his fellow executives were released following the settlement.
In 2008 a civil lawsuit in London was launched by almost 30,000 Ivorians against Trafigura. In May 2009 Trafigura announced it would sue the BBC for libel after its Newsnight program alleged the company had knowingly sought to cover up its role in the incident. In September 2009 The Guardian obtained and published internal Trafigura emails showing that the traders responsible knew how dangerous the chemicals were. Shortly afterwards Trafigura agreed to a settlement of ¬£30 million (US$42.4 million) to settle the suit.[In 2010 a Dutch court found Trafigura guilty of illegally exporting toxic waste from Amsterdam.

(NDTV)
Paris Saint-Germain president Nasser Al-Khelaifi and former FIFA number two Jerome Valcke to face prison for alleged corruption in the allocation of World Cup TV rights. Valcke sought the Qatari's help in the summer of 2003 to buy a luxury villa in Sardinia, at a time when beIN, a Qatari-owned broadcaster, was negotiating the extension of its media rights in North Africa and the Middle East for the 2026 and 2030 World Cups.

(MY comment) Most people would probably guess it was not your first shake down if you demand a luxury villa as, alleged, bribe! FIFA....again! The neutrality here seems to be the usual, we take, allegedly, bribes from everyone in this nation!

(Fortune)
Credit Suisse report into $5.5 billion Archegos loss shows bank has a massive culture problem

(ABC, 2005) 
ABC Radio reported in 2005 that Glencore "has been accused of illegal dealings with rogue states: apartheid South Africa, USSR, Iran, and Iraq under Saddam Hussein", and has a "history of busting UN embargoes to profit from corrupt or despotic regimes". Specifically, the CIA found that Glencore had paid $3,222,780 in illegal kickbacks to obtain oil in the course of the UN oil-for-food programme for Iraq

(Wiki)
Western Sahara
In 2013 and 2014, a subsidiary of Glencore Xstrata was awarded two offshore drilling licenses off the coast of occupied Western Sahara. The licenses are awarded in clear violation of international law, as described by the UN in 2002.

The 2006 C√¥te d'Ivoire toxic waste dump was a health crisis in C√¥te d'Ivoire in which the Probo Koala, a ship registered in Panama and chartered by Trafigura, hired a local contractor to offload waste in Abidjan after refusing to pay a ‚Ç¨1,000 per cubic metre surcharge imposed by Amsterdam Port Services to discourage waste disposal in the Netherlands. The local contractor, Tommy, improperly dumped the waste materials at as many as 12 sites in and around the city of Abidjan in August 2006. The gas caused by the release of these chemicals is blamed by the UN and the government of C√¥te d'Ivoire for the deaths of 17 and the injury of over 30,000 Ivorians, with injuries that ranged from mild headaches to severe burns of skin and lungs. Almost 100,000 Ivorians sought medical attention.  
Trafigura maintains that the substance dumped consisted of "slops", or waste water from washing the Probo Koala's tanks. An inquiry in the Netherlands, in late 2006, confirmed the substance to consist of more than 500 tonnes of a mix of fuel, hydrogen sulfide, and sodium hydroxide, known as caustic soda.
Trafigura denied any waste was transported from the Netherlands, saying that the substances contained only tiny amounts of hydrogen sulfide, and that the company did not know the substance was to be disposed of improperly. Trafigura officials, including Claude Dauphin and the company‚Äôs West Africa regional director, traveled to Abidjan to assist in the cleanup effort but were arrested and imprisoned by the Ivorian government. While its executives were being held, the company agreed to pay US$198 million for cleanup to the Ivorian government without admitting wrongdoing, and the Ivorian government pledged not to prosecute the company.[Dauphin and his fellow executives were released following the settlement.
In 2008 a civil lawsuit in London was launched by almost 30,000 Ivorians against Trafigura. In May 2009 Trafigura announced it would sue the BBC for libel after its Newsnight program alleged the company had knowingly sought to cover up its role in the incident. text:
Alex, you are absolutely right. However, Switzerland has, by far the largest numbers of peaks in the Alps over 4'000 m high. Yes, the Mt Blanc is between France and Italy, but it's very close to the Swiss border, and around the Mt Blanc, mountains are otherwise not so high. The highest areas of the Alps are the Monte Rosa area (near Zermatt, Switzerland, and bordering with Italy, but most of the high peaks are on the Swiss side), the Jungfrau Area, the Gotthard area. All in Switzerland. So overall it is still fair to say that Switzerland is the top of the Europe. 

As for the cable car and train in this video, to call it "Top of Europe" is a bit of a marketing gimmick. The highest cable car or train are in Zermatt (Klein Matterhorn, which is almost 300 m higher than the Jungfraujoch) and the Allalin Glacier in Saas Fee.

text:
As a Swiss I have a few remarks
- Firstly, and most importantly,  I'm very glad you liked your stay.
- Secondly, the Top of Europe: The Jungfraujoch is actually not the highest point of Europe or Switzerland, there are plenty of higher places, but the highest train station. And all in all quite a great experience.
- Thridly, the salaries: While salaries, household income, individual wealth et cetera are certainly very high, the average income isn't quite 120'000 dollars, but rather atound 78'000 Swiss Francs (circa 85'000USD).
- Minimum salary: Actually, Switzerland doesn't have a minimum income. A handful of cantons do have one on a cantonal level.

Apart from that I really liked the video and think you conveyed great, what I like most about Switzerland: All the action you can have. If you ever visit again, I recommend you consider visiting Bern for a nice old town and/or the canton of Ticino (which btw is a canyoning eldorado).

text:
‚Äã¬†@syblsvideos¬† Are you perhaps forgetting to mention that the 4'500 CHF per month is for a 70% job or something of that sort?

Perhaps you should also tell those foreigners that the average income per PERSON in Switzerland  is 6'500 CHF/ Month for a 100% job - and this includes 19 - 26 year olds just starting their working lives. That would put your lower salary into perspective, as it could indicate that either you are only working part-time (understandable with two kids) or at the bottom of the earnings scale where mainly uneducated workers are employed.

To give an unbiased picture of the salary situation in a country, it is not advisable to use only your personal situation and then leave out half of the information.

If you are single mom with two kids and the sole earner making only that low a salary despite working 100%, then you might have additional income from the children's father that you "forgot" to mention, or support payments from the local town where you would be registered as a social benefits recipient.
In any case, your example is possibly "incomplete" or not truely transparent.

I'm not advocating you disclose all information here. But to use your example of your self-perceived "bad" salary situation, while perhaps leaving out pertinent information, does a poor service to those you are supposedly trying to educate, as Tsotne just belows proves with her comments.
